<TEI xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0" xmlns:frus="http://history.state.gov/frus/ns/1.0"><text><body><div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1885-02-27T23:59:59-05:00" frus:doc-dateTime-min="1885-02-27T00:00:00-05:00" n="579" subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d579">
                        <opener><seg rendition="#center">No. 579.</seg></opener>
                        <head><hi rend="italic">Mr. <persName type="from">Frelinghuysen</persName>
                                to Mr. <persName type="to">Valera</persName></hi>.</head>
                        <opener><dateline rendition="#right"><placeName><hi rend="smallcaps">Department of State</hi>,<lb/><hi rend="italic">Washington</hi></placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1885-02-27"><hi rend="italic">February</hi> 27,
                                    1885</date>.</dateline></opener>
                        <p><hi rend="smallcaps">Sir</hi>: Referring to quite recent correspondence,
                            touching a report of the establishment at Key West of a lottery in the
                            interest of political adventurers having designs against the peace of
                            Cuba, I have the honor to say that according to a letter of the
                            Postmaster-General, founded on official reports of his Department, there
                            is discovered no foundation for the rumor in question.</p>
                        <p>Accept, &amp;c.,</p>
                        <closer><signed>FRED’K T. FRELINGHUYSEN.</signed></closer>
                    </div>
                    </body></text></TEI>